TextChange: If one highly successful employee receives the new position and a raise, their competitor may leave and look for better benefits at another company.
Extra effort deserves extra compensation. The winner shouldn't be the only one receiving all the benefits.

Leaders don't necessary contribute to the overall success of a team. They may work to ease deadlines when necessary, but they don't have the skills to achieve the best results by themselves. In some cases, an underqualified leader can even lower the success of a team. Discouraging or outdated leaders can drive employees away, increasing turnover rate and creating a hostile work environment. Leadership is a necessary part of working. However, this leadership is only effective if it serves to benefit and improve the existing skills of the team. Focusing on leaderships itself as the most important factor leaves employees, the true backbone of the company, to falter and find work elsewhere.

The older generation no longer has the technological skills to keep up. They assign simple tasks to their employees like working with Excel or firewalling their system because they themselves don't know how to do it.

Employees aren't able to respect their leaders if they believe they're more qualified. The new workforce has just left their training or education. They may not yet have experience, but they know how to handle day-to-day tasks like emailing, outlining projects and working with clients. Leadership falls flat if employees can handle every other part of the project are only need their team leader's permission to move forward. Leadership is an essential part of a successful work environment, but it needs to be able to keep up with its employees.   => T
